@rudderstack/analytics-js  (RudderStack JS analytics SDK)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Used by:        renderer product analytics (`src/renderer/src/analytics.ts`)
                — COMMERCIAL builds only.
Source:         https://www.npmjs.com/package/@rudderstack/analytics-js
License:        Elastic License 2.0 (ELv2)

Licensing notice:
  `@rudderstack/analytics-js` is Elastic-2.0 (source-available, not OSI
  open-source). It is a COMMERCIAL-BUILD-ONLY dependency: the commercial
  renderer loads it via a guarded, brace-nested dynamic `import()` in
  `src/renderer/src/analytics.ts` (code-split, not statically inlined). It is
  EXCLUDED from the public/OSS mirror — stripped from the public `package.json`
  and lockfiles (`mirror/substitutions.yaml#dependency_strips`) and resolved to
  a local no-op stub (`src/renderer/src/oss/rudderstack-analytics-stub.ts`) via a
  build alias — so it is in neither the public manifest nor the OSS renderer
  bundle. Note this is the package LICENSE question only — it is distinct from
  any phone-home concern, which is separately gated: in OSS builds analytics is
  opt-in and the client is never constructed unless the user opts in with their
  own keys (see `src/renderer/src/analytics.ossGate.test.ts`).

  ELv2's restrictions are (i) do not provide the software to third parties as a
  hosted/managed service, (ii) do not circumvent license-key functionality, and
  (iii) preserve notices. Because the Elastic-2.0 package is excluded from the
  public OSS mirror entirely, the source-available repo carries no Elastic-2.0
  dependency; the commercial Rebel desktop app (not offered as a hosted
  RudderStack-competing service) does not appear to trip these — but this is a
  legal read.

  Status: the OSS-exclusion (the "make the SDK optional so OSS builds need not
  bundle it" should-have) is DONE — see OSS_TODO §7 "Minimal license-only fix"
  and the dependency_strips entry above. The commercial-build legal read remains
  pending written legal sign-off (low risk; the redistribution-in-source read
